06525nam a22008295i 9781442694439DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182012onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426944397 a10.3138/97814426944392doi  a(DE-B1597)497110  a(OCoLC)1078919898  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0260102bisacsh04a340.5/9097122300aDebating Sharia :bIslam, Gender Politics, and Family Law Arbitration /ced. by Anna Korteweg, Jennifer Selby. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Situating the Sharia Debate -- tForeword: Sharia and the Future of Western Secularism -- tIntroduction: Situating the Sharia Debate in Ontario -- tPart One: Practising Religious Divorce among North American Muslims -- t1. Practising an ‘Islamic Imagination’: Islamic Divorce in North America -- t2. Faith-Based Arbitration or Religious Divorce: What Was the Issue? -- tPart Two: Regulating Faith-Based Arbitration -- t3. Multiculturalism Meets Privatization: The Case of Faith-Based Arbitration -- t4. ‘Sharia’ Courts in Canada: A Delayed Opportunity for the Indigenization of Islamic Legal Rulings -- t5. Asking Questions about Sharia: Lessons from Ontario -- t6. Islamic Law and the Canadian Mosaic: Politics, Jurisprudence, and Multicultural Accommodation -- tPart Four: Negotiating the Politics of Sharia-Based Arbitration -- t7. The ‘Good’ Muslim, ‘Bad’ Muslim Puzzle? The Assertion of Muslim Women’s Islamic Identity in the Sharia Debates in Canada -- t8. ‘The Muslims Have Ruined Our Party’: A Case Study of Ontario Media Portrayals of Supporters of Faith-Based Arbitration -- tPart Five: Analysing Discourses of Race, Gender, and Religion -- t9. Sharia in Canada? Mapping Discourses of Race, Gender, and Religious Difference -- t10. Agency and Representations: Voices and Silences in the Ontario Sharia Debate -- tPart Six: Managing Religion in the Canadian State -- t11. Managing the Mosaic: The Work of Form in ‘Dispute Resolution in Family Law: Protecting Choice, Promoting Inclusion -- t12. Construing the Secular: Implications of the Ontario Sharia Debate -- tConcluding Thoughts -- tConclusion: Debating Sharia in the West -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the Islamic Institute of Civil Justice announced it would begin offering Sharia-based services in Ontario, a subsequent provincial government review gave qualified support for religious arbitration. However, the ensuing debate inflamed the passions of a wide range of Muslim and non-Muslim groups, garnered worldwide attention, and led to a ban on religiously based family law arbitration in the province. Debating Sharia sheds light on how Ontario&apos;s Sharia debate of 2003-2006 exemplified contemporary concerns regarding religiosity in the public sphere and the place of Islam in Western nation states.Focusing on the legal ramifications of Sharia law in the context of rapidly changing Western liberal democracies, Debating Sharia approaches the issue from a variety of methodological perspectives, including policy and media analysis, fieldwork, feminist examinations of the portrayals of Muslim women, and theoretical examinations of religion, Sharia, and the law. This volume is an important read for those who grapple with ethnic and religio-cultural diversity while remaining committed to religious freedom and women&apos;s equality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIslamic lawzCanada. 0aMuslimsxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aMuslimsxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marria